#1. Plot the distributions of all the numerical columns in the dataset using
#histograms.

import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import math

# Number of numerical columns
n_cols = len(numerical_cols)

# Set number of columns per row
cols_per_row = 3
rows = math.ceil(n_cols / cols_per_row)

plt.figure(figsize=(15, rows * 4))

for i, col in enumerate(numerical_cols, 1):
    plt.subplot(rows, cols_per_row, i)
    sns.histplot(df[col], bins=30, kde=True)
    plt.title(f'Distribution of {col}')
    plt.xlabel(col)
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

#2. Plot the distributions of all the numerical columns in the dataset using box
#plots.


import math
import seaborn as sns
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Number of numerical columns
n_cols = len(numerical_cols)

# Number of plots per row
plots_per_row = 4

# Calculate required rows
rows = math.ceil(n_cols / plots_per_row)

# Create figure
plt.figure(figsize=(16, rows * 4))

for i, col in enumerate(numerical_cols, 1):
    plt.subplot(rows, plots_per_row, i)
    sns.boxplot(y=df[col])
    plt.title(f'Box Plot of {col}')
    plt.ylabel(col)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

#6.Which areas (neighbourhoods) have the highest availability?
# Ensure Min Nights is numeric
df['Min Nights'] = pd.to_numeric(df['Min Nights'], errors='coerce')

min_nights_df = df.dropna(subset=['Min Nights', 'neighbourhood'])

mean_min_nights = (
    min_nights_df
    .groupby('neighbourhood')['Min Nights']
    .mean()
    .sort_values(ascending=False)
    .head(10)
)

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
mean_min_nights.plot(kind='bar')

plt.title('Neighbourhoods with Highest Minimum Night Requirements')
plt.xlabel('Neighbourhood')
plt.ylabel('Average Minimum Nights')

plt.xticks(rotation=45, ha='right')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

#7.Superhost vs non-superhost pricing
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# clean Price column (remove $ and commas if present)
df['Price'] = df['Price'].replace('[\$,]', '', regex=True).astype(float)

# drop missing values
filtered_df = df[['Is Superhost', 'Price']].dropna()

# plot
plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
filtered_df.boxplot(column='Price', by='Is Superhost')
plt.title('Superhost vs Non-Superhost Pricing')
plt.suptitle('')
plt.xlabel('Is Superhost (True = Superhost)')

def get_season(month):
    if pd.isna(month):
        return None
    elif month in [12, 1, 2]:
        return 'Winter'
    elif month in [3, 4, 5]:
        return 'Spring'
    elif month in [6, 7, 8]:
        return 'Summer'
    else:
        return 'Autumn'

df['season'] = df['month'].apply(get_season)
